AGI&nbsp; - It is a clash in the Hague on the 'universal disorder' proposed by the president of Figc Gabriele Gravina to elect the head of the association of arbitrators. It would be up to all whistles, about 30 thousand, to designate their representative that is now chosen by the 340 presidents of section and delegates.
As the AGI learns, after the perplexities expressed by the current president Carlo Pacifici, in response to Gravina, a current emerged within the National Aia Committee, led by Antonio Zappi and Michele Affinito, ready to support a proposal of ‘compromise’, which would however preview an extension of the electoral base, in view of the examination of the issue previewed tomorrow in the Council of Figc.
&nbsp;
The idea is that of a system in which electoral delegates, about 1000 compared to the current 340, would decide the fortunes of the election, including section presidents who would enter the list. A proposal that, according to the promoters, would avoid demagogic myres, which would favor potentially candidates such as Gianluca Rocchi and Daniele Orsato considered close to Gravina and his 'right arm', lawyer Giancarlo Viglione.&nbsp;
Yesterday Pacifici had expressed his “amarezza” on the novelty hoped by Gravina, not so much on the merit as on the modalities. “I think such an important change should be shared (we are a few days ago outraged by a unilateral act of the government) and not formulated in details and put to the vote by prevading those elements that should always accompany change.” However, as reported by some newspapers, Figc argued that Pacifici would actually share the draft reform on universal suffrage. &nbsp;

